    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "## Code Review\n\nReviewed Windows PTY implementation fix for CLI testing. The approach is sound - splitting PTY creation into two paths (pipe-based for `Attach()` and ConPTY for `Start()`) addresses the root cause of test flakiness on Windows. Found 1 minor issue regarding error handling consistency and 1 documentation clarification.\n\n### Summary\n\n**Positive:**\n- Correctly identifies that ConPTY requires a real process and fails intermittently without one\n- Clean separation of concerns between pipe-based PTY (for tests) and ConPTY (for real processes)\n- `pipePty` properly implements the `PTY` interface\n- Good comments explaining the rationale for the split\n- Appropriate mutex protection for close operations\n\n**Issues:**\n- Minor: Inconsistent error handling pattern in `pipePty.Close()` compared to `ptyWindows.Close()`\n- Minor: Return type change from `*ptyWindows` to `PTY` could use clarification in comments\n\n### Details\n\nThe fix correctly addresses the problem: Windows ConPTY (`PseudoConsole`) requires an attached process to function correctly. When `ptytest.New()` is used with `Attach()` for in-process CLI testing, no real process exists, causing pipe handles to become invalid intermittently.\n\nThe solution is elegant:\n1. `newPty()` returns a simple pipe-based `PTY` implementation for the `Attach()` use case\n2. `newConPty()` creates a real ConPTY, called by `Start()` when a process will be attached\n3. The `pipePty` type properly implements the `PTY` interface with no-op `Resize()` and clean pipe management\n\nThe implementation correctly handles the pipe cleanup order (close writers before readers to avoid blocking).",
